 performance as a base, with incremental amounts added for the new budget period. Adjustments are made for expected changes such as inflation, planned increases in sales prices, and costs. This method is straightforward, easy, and quick to perform, making it suitable for stable environments. However, it can encourage inefficiency, carry forward errors, and may not be suitable for volatile industries due to its less flexible nature.\",10\n865,\"\"\"BUDGETARY CONTROL SYSTEM\"\"\",,7\n856,\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET\"\" is a continuous budgeting process where the budget is updated regularly, typically every quarter, to reflect changes in the market and business environment. This approach is more flexible and responsive to changes compared to traditional annual budgets. A rolling budget is continuously updated and is most suitable in a rapidly changing environment where the original budget quickly becomes outdated.\",3\n2152,\"\"\"TIMANA CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Timana Co manufactures small-panel display screens for various consumer electronic products. The company faces challenges in a competitive industry with short product life cycles and pricing pressures. The finance director has proposed shifting from incremental budgeting to a rolling budget approach to better adapt to market changes.\"\"\",2\n828,\"\"\"USEFULNESS OF INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"Incremental budgeting may be appropriate for a stable business with good cost control. Managers need only justify the increments. The system is relatively simple to operate and easy to understand. Conflicts should be avoided if departments can be seen to be treated similarly. Coordination between budgets is easier to achieve, as increments in functional budgets are easily aggregated into master budgets. The effect of change can be seen quickly.\"\"\",1\n829,\"\"\"PROBLEMS WITH INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"Incremental budgeting assumes activities and methods of working will continue in the same way regardless of whether they are needed. It gives no incentive for developing new ways of working or the reduction of costs. It encourages a 'spend it or lose' mentality so that the budget is maintained next year. The budget may become out of date and no longer relate to the level of activity or type of work being carried out. The priority for resources may have changed since the budgets were set originally. Any budgetary slack in a previous budget is not reviewed. It is also easier to add and justify budgetary slack to make achieving budgets easier. When a budgeting system has been in operation for some time, there is a tendency for the following year's budget to be justified by referencing the levels currently being achieved. However, the analysis process should consider all changes affecting the organisation's future activities. Even using such an analytical base, some organisations find that historical comparisons, particularly the current resource constraints, can inhibit innovative budget changes. This can severely handicap an organisation because the budget should be the first year of the long-term strategic plan. If changes are not started in the budget period, it will be more difficult for the organisation to make the progress necessary to achieve long-term objectives.\"\"\",1\n857,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED BUDGETING (ABB)\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity-based budgets use ABC principles to calculate the budgeted overhead costs.\"\"\",1\n858,\"\"\"BEYOND BUDGETING MODEL\"\"\",\"\"\"The Beyond Budgeting model aims to replace traditional budgetary control systems with a more modern approach which replaces financial targets with key performance indicators.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n682,\"\"\"INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"BUDGETARY CONTROL SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"Incremental budgeting is a traditional approach used within a budgetary control system that bases next year\u2019s budget on the current year's budget or actual figures.\"\"\",17\n691,\"\"\"ZERO-BASED BUDGETING (ZBB)\"\"\",\"\"\"BUDGETARY CONTROL SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"Zero-based budgeting (ZBB) is a method used within a budgetary control system that starts 'from scratch' and requires all costs and benefits to be justified.\"\"\",16\n683,\"\"\"INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"ZERO-BASED BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"Incremental budgeting and zero-based budgeting are two different approaches to budgeting.\"\"\",14\n687,\"\"\"INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"YUMI CO'S BUDGETING PROCESS\"\"\",\"\"\"Incremental budgeting is currently used in Yumi Co's budgeting process.\"\"\",14\n685,\"\"\"INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"NEWTOWN SCHOOL BUDGETING PROCESS\"\"\",\"\"\"Incremental budgeting is discussed as part of Newtown School's budgeting process for the year ending 31 May 20X5.\"\"\",13\n686,\"\"\"INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"COWLY RESTAURANT BUDGET ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"The Cowly restaurant budget analysis discusses whether an incremental approach to budgeting is appropriate for Yumi Co.\"\"\",13\n688,\"\"\"INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET\"\"\",\"\"\"Rolling budget is proposed as a more flexible alternative to the current incremental budgeting method used by Timana Co.\"\"\",13\n684,\"\"\"INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"BUDGETING APPROACHES AT NEWTOWN SCHOOL\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of Budgeting Approaches at Newtown School involves the use of incremental budgeting.\"\"\",12\n689,\"\"\"INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"TIMANA CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Timana Co currently uses incremental budgeting, which is less flexible and not suitable for the volatile technology industry.\"\"\",12\n672,\"\"\"BOTTOM-UP BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"BUDGETARY CONTROL SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"Bottom-up budgeting is a method used within a budgetary control system where departments participate in preparing their own budgets.\"\"\",11\n680,\"\"\"INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"USEFULNESS OF INCREMENTAL BUDGETING\"\"\",\"\"\"Usefulness of Incremental Budgeting d